 Introduction to Package Manager

A Package Manager is a software tool that automates the process of installing, updating, configuring, and removing software packages or libraries required for an application. In modern software development, applications depend on many external libraries to perform specific tasks such as database connectivity, authentication, networking, data processing, and user interface design.

Instead of downloading and configuring each library manually, developers use a package manager to handle these tasks efficiently. It also keeps track of package versions, resolves dependency conflicts, and ensures that all required components are installed correctly.

Package managers improve development speed, maintain project consistency, and simplify collaboration among team members.

